 The place is the American south in the mid-20th century, and before we meet its people we learn, from Harrington\u2019s intense, cadence-driven lines, that we will be reading a poetry that calls out and sings to the world. The propulsive Alexandrine opening couplet of The Thief\u2019s Tabernacle, which begins the collection, marks Harrington as the most rhythmically driven of these three poets...<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gentlyread.wordpress.com/2009/01/01/three-new-poets-i-met-at-bread-loaf-by-steve-wingate/| title=Three New Poets I Met at Bread Loaf |author=Steve Wingate| date=2009-01-01| work=Gently Read Lit }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|African Americans}}\n* {{official website }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100308064113/http://poetlaureate.il.gov/featuredpoet_harrington.cfm \"Featured Illinois Poet\"], selected by the Illinois Poet Laureate\n* {{LCAuth|n94040410|Janice N. Harrington|6|}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrington, Janice}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign faculty]]\n[[Category:Poets from Alabama]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:American women children's writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Rona Jaffe Foundation Writers' Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "'''Janice N. Harrington''' is an American [[poet]] and children's writer.\n\n==Life==\nShe grew up in Alabama and Nebraska.\n\nShe worked as a public librarian in [[Champaign, Illinois]], and as a professional storyteller, appearing at the [[National Storytelling Festival]].<ref>[http://boaeditions.org/authors/harrington.html Could Not Find \u2013 Authors] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081105155437/http://boaeditions.org/authors/harrington.html |date=2008-11-05 }}. BOA Editions. Retrieved on 2010-12-01.</