(United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Minnesota]]: [[Lou Wangberg]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Mississippi]]: [[Brad Dye]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Missouri]]: [[William C. Phelps]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 12), [[Kenneth Rothman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 12)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Montana]]: [[Ted Schwinden]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 5), [[George Turman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 5)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Nebraska]]: [[Roland A. Luedtke]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Nevada]]: [[Myron E. Leavitt]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico]]: [[Roberto Mondrag\u00f3n]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of New York]]: [[Mario Cuomo]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of North Carolina]]: [[James C. Green]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of North Dakota]]: [[Wayne G. Sanstead]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until month and day unknown), [[Ernest Sands]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting month and day unknown)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Ohio]]: vacant\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Oklahoma]]: [[Spencer Bernard (politician)|Spencer Bernard]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Pennsylvania]]: [[William Scranton, III]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Rhode Island]]: [[Thomas R. DiLuglio]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of South Carolina]]: [[Nancy Stevenson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of South Dakota]]: [[Lowell C. Hansen II]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Tennessee]]: [[John S. Wilder]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Texas]]: [[William P. Hobby Jr.]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Utah]]: [[David Smith Monson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Vermont]]: [[Madeleine M. Kunin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Virginia]]: [[Chuck Robb]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Washington]]: [[John Cherberg]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Wisconsin]]: [[Russell A. Olson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n}}\n|}\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n[[File:Official Portrait of President Reagan 1981.jpg|thumb|right|120px|January 20: [[Ronald Reagan]] becomes President]]\n[[File:Iran hostages return.jpg|thumb|right|120px|January 20: The [[Iran hostage crisis]] ends with their release]]\n* January 19 &ndash; United States and [[Iran]]ian officials sign an agreement to release 52 American [[hostage]]s after 14 months of [[Imprisonment|captivity]].\n* January 20 &ndash; [[Ronald Reagan]] is sworn in as the 40th [[President of the United States]]. Minutes later, [[Iran]] releases the 52 Americans held for 444 days, ending the [[Iran hostage crisis]].\n* January 25 &ndash; [[Super Bowl XV]]: The [[Oakland Raiders]] defeat the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] 27\u201310 at the [[Louisiana Superdome]] in [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]].\n\n===February===\n* February 10 &ndash; A fire at the [[Las Vegas Hilton]] [[hotel]]-[[casino]] kills 8 and injures 198.\n\n===March===\n[[File:President Ronald Reagan moments before he was shot in an assassination attempt 1981.jpg|thumb|right|120px|March 30: [[Reagan assassination attempt]]]]\n* March 6 &ndash; After 19 years hosting the ''[[CBS Evening News]]'', [[Walter Cronkite]] signs off for the last time.\n* March 19 &ndash; Three workers are killed and 5 injured during a test of the [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']].\n* March 21 &ndash;  [[Michael Donald]] [[lynched]].\n* March 30 &ndash; U.S. President [[Ronald Reagan]] is [[Reagan assassination attempt|shot in the chest]] outside a [[Washington, D.C.]]  hotel by [[John Hinckley, Jr.]] Two police officers and Press Secretary [[James Brady]] are also wounded.\n* March 31 &ndash; The [[53rd Academy Awards]], hosted by [[Johnny Carson]], are held at the [[Dorothy Chandler Pavilion]] in [[Los Angeles]]. [[Robert Redford]]'s directorial debut in ''[[Ordinary People]]'' wins [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]].\n\n===April===\n[[File:Space Shuttle Columbia launching.jpg|thumb|right|120px|April 12: The first [[STS-1|Space Shuttle]] launch]]\n* April 12 &ndash; The [[Space Shuttle]] program: ''[[Space Shuttle Columbia]]'' ([[Johhhm Young (astronaut)|John Young]], [[Robert Crippen]]) launches on the [[STS-1]] mission, returning to Earth on April 14.\n* April 18 &ndash; A [[Minor League Baseball]] game between the [[Rochester Red Wings]] and the [[Pawtucket Red Sox]] at [[McCoy Stadium]] in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island]], becomes the [[longest professional baseball game]] in history: 8 hours and 25 minutes/33 innings (the 33rd inning is not played until June 23).\n* April 26 &ndash; The 5.9 {{M|w|link=y}} [[List of earthquakes in California|Westmorland earthquake]] shook the [[Imperial Valley]] of California with a maximum [[Mercalli intensity scale|Mercalli intensity]] of VII (''Very strong''), causing $1\u20133 million in damage.\n\n===May===\n* May 15 &ndash; [[Donna Payant]] is murdered by serial killer [[Lemuel Smith]], the first time a female prison officer has been killed on-duty in the United States.\n\n===June===\n* June &ndash; The United States enters the severe [[early 1980s recession]], exactly a year after the more minor 1980 recession ended; the unemployment rate is 7.2%\n* June 5 &ndash; The [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] report that five [[homosexuality|homosexual]] men in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], have a rare form of [[pneumonia]] seen only in patients with weakened [[immune system]]s (the first recognized cases of [[AIDS]]).\n* June 12 &ndash; [[Major League Baseball]] goes on [[1981 Major League Baseball strike|strike]], forcing the cancellation of 38 percent of the schedule.\n* June 21 &ndash; [[Wayne Williams]], a 23-year-old [[African American]], is arrested and charged with the murders of two other [[African Americans]]. He is later accused of 28 others, in the [[Atlanta child murders]].\n* June 29 &ndash; Morris Edwin Robert, armed with a machine gun, holds hostages in the FBI section at the [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] Federal Building. After three hours, the hostages are rescued and Robert is killed in a shootout with federal agents.\n\n===July===\n[[File:Hyatt Regency collapse floor view.PNG|thumb|right|120px|July 17: [[Hyatt Regency walkway collapse]]]]\n* July 7 &ndash; [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] nominates the first woman, [[Sandra Day O'Connor]], to the [[Supreme Court of the United States]].\n* July 8 &ndash; [[California]] Governor [[Jerry Brown]], faced with a [[Mediterranean fruit fly]] infestation, chooses to delay the aerial spraying of [[malathion]], in favor of continuing ground-based eradication efforts.\n* July 9 &ndash; First release of [[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]] and first debut of [[Mario (franchise)|Mario]].\n* July 17 \n**[[Hyatt Regency walkway collapse]]: Two skywalks filled with people at the Hyatt Regency Hotel in [[Kansas City, Missouri]] collapse into a crowded atrium lobby, killing 114.\n**[[Israel]]i aircraft bomb [[Beirut]], [[Lebanese Civil War#Israeli bombing of Beirut|destroying multi-story apartment blocks]] containing the offices of [[PLO]] associated groups, killing approximately 300 civilians and resulting in worldwide condemnation and a U.S. embargo on the export of aircraft to Israel.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Bombing of Beirut|journal=Journal of Palestine Studies|volume=11|issue=1|year=1981|pages=218\u2013225|doi=10.1525/jps.1981.11.1.00p0366x}}</ref>\n* July 27 &ndash; [[Murder of Adam Walsh|Adam Walsh]], 6, is kidnapped from a Sears store in Hollywood, Florida.\n\n===August===\n* August 1 &ndash; [[MTV]] (Music Television) is launched on cable television in the United States.\n* August 5 &ndash; U.S. President [[Ronald Reagan]] fires 11,359 [[Strike action|striking]] [[air-traffic controller]]s who ignored his order for them to return to work.\n* August 7 &ndash; ''The [[Washington Star]]'' ceases publication after 128 years.\n* August 9 &ndash; [[Major League Baseball]] resumes from [[1981 Major League Baseball strike|the strike]] with the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]]'s [[Cleveland Stadium|Municipal Stadium]].\n* August 10 &ndash; Exactly two weeks after his disappearance, the severed head of 6-year-old [[Hollywood, Florida]] native [[Murder of Adam Walsh|Adam Walsh]] is found in a canal in [[Vero Beach, Florida]]; to this day the rest of the boy's body has never been recovered.\n* August 12 &ndash; The original Model 5150 [[IBM PC]] (with a 4.77&nbsp;MHz [[Intel 8088]] processor) is released in the United States at a base price of $1,565.\n* August 19 \n**[[Gulf of Sidra incident (1981)]]: [[Libya]]n leader [[Muammar al-Gaddafi]] sends 2 [[Sukhoi Su-22]] fighter jets to intercept 2 U.S. fighters over the [[Gulf of Sidra]]. The American jets destroy the Libyan fighters.\n**U.S. President [[Ronald Reagan]] appoints the first female U.S. Supreme Court Justice, [[Sandra Day O'Connor]].\n* August 24 &ndash; [[Mark David Chapman]] is sentenced to 20 years to life in prison, after being convicted of murdering [[John Lennon]] in [[Manhattan]] eight months earlier.\n* August 31 &ndash; A bomb explodes at the [[Ramstein Air Base|U.S. Air Force base in Ramstein]], [[West Germany]], injuring 20 people.\n\n===September===\n* September 10 &ndash; [[Picasso]]'s painting \"[[Guernica (painting)|Guernica]]\" is moved from [[New York City]] to [[Madrid]].\n* September 11 &ndash; A small plane crashes into the [[Swing Auditorium]] in [[San Bernardino, California]], damaging the venue beyond repair.\n* September 15 &ndash; The ''[[John Bull (locomotive)|John Bull]]'' becomes the oldest operable [[steam locomotive]] in the world, at 150 years old, when it operates under its own power outside [[Washington, DC]].\n* September 17 &ndash; [[Ric Flair]] defeats Dusty Rhodes to win his first World Heavyweight Wrestling Championship in [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]].\n* September 19 &ndash; [[Simon & Garfunkel]] perform [[The Concert in Central Park]], a free concert in New York in front of approximately half a million people.\n* September 25 \n**[[Sandra Day O'Connor]] takes her seat as the first female justice of the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].\n**[[The Rolling Stones]] begin their [[Tattoo You]] tour at [[JFK Stadium]] in [[Philadelphia]].\n\n===October===\n* October 28 &ndash; The [[Thrash metal music|thrash metal]] band [[Metallica]] forms in [[Los Angeles]].\n** The [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] defeat the [[New York Yankees]], 4 games to 2, to win their 5th World Series Title.\n\n===November===\n* November 12 &ndash; [[STS-2]]: [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']] ([[Joe Engle]], [[Richard Truly]]) lifts off for its second mission.\n* November 16 &ndash; Luke and Laura marry on the U.S. soap opera ''[[General Hospital]]''; it is the highest-rated hour in daytime television history.\n* November 23 &ndash; [[Iran-Contra scandal]]: [[Ronald Reagan]] signs the [[Classified information|top secret]] National Security Decision Directive 17 (NSDD-17), authorizing the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] to recruit and support [[Contras|Contra]] rebels in [[Nicaragua]].\n* November 30 &ndash; [[Cold War]]: In [[Geneva]], representatives from the United States and the [[Soviet Union]] begin negotiating intermediate-range [[nuclear weapon]] reductions in [[Europe]] (the meetings end inconclusively on Thursday, December 17).\n\n===December===\n\n* December 5 &ndash; American general [[James L. Dozier]] is kidnapped in [[Verona]] by the Italian [[Red Brigades]].\n* December 8 &ndash; The [[No. 21 Mine explosion]] in [[Whitwell, Tennessee]] kills 13.\n* December 11 &ndash; [[Boxing]]: [[Muhammad Ali]] loses to [[Trevor Berbick]]; this proved to be Ali's last-ever fight.\n* December 28 &ndash; The first American [[test-tube baby]], [[Elizabeth Jordan Carr]], is born in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].\n\n===Ongoing===\n* [[Cold War]] (1947\u20131991)\n* [[Iran hostage crisis]] (1979\u20131981)\n* [[Early 1980s recession]] (1981\u20131982)\n\n==Births==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* January 1 &ndash; [[Eden Riegel]], actress\n* January 2 &ndash; [[Kirk Hinrich]], basketball player\n* January 4\n** [[Alicia Garza]], activist \n** [[Aaron Schwartz (American actor)|Aaron Schwartz]], actor\n* January 6 &ndash; [[Camila Grey]], singer-songwriter and guitarist\n* January 7 &ndash; [[Marquis Daniels]], basketball player\n* January 9 &ndash; [[Caroline Lufkin]], singer\n* January 10 &ndash; [[Brian Joo]], R&B singer\n* January 12 &ndash; [[Quentin Griffin]], American football player\n* January 17 [[Ray J]] Rapper and Singer\n* January 20 Jason Richardson - basketball Player\n* January 22 Ben Moody - guitarist\n* January 25 Alicia Keys, - singer, pianist and actress\n* January 28 Elijah Wood, actor and music producer\n* January 29 &ndash; [[Jonny Lang]], musician\n* January 31 &ndash; [[Justin Timberlake]], singer-songwriter, actor and record producer\n* February 1 &ndash; [[John Gemberling]], actor and comedian\n* February 6 &ndash; [[Alison Haislip]], actress and former TV personality\n* February 9 The Rev drummer (d. 2009)\n* February 14 &ndash; [[Erin Torpey]], actress\n* February 17 &ndash; [[Joseph Gordon-Levitt]], actor, director, producer and writer\n* February 18 &ndash; [[Kamasi Washington]], crossover jazz saxophonist\n* February 20 &ndash; [[Chris Thile]], mandolinist\n* February 26 &ndash; [[Maria Sansone]], journalist and Internet personality\n* March 1 &ndash; [[Brad Winchester]], ice hockey player\n* March 9 \u2013 Antonio Bryant, football player\n* March 17 [[Kyle Korver]] basketball player\n* March 25 &ndash; [[Casey Neistat]], YouTube personality\n* April 12 &ndash; [[Tulsi Gabbard]], politician\n* April 13 &ndash; [[Courtney Peldon]], actress\n* April 16 &ndash; [[Jake Scott (guard)|Jake Scott]], American football player\n* April 22 [[Ken Dorsey]] football player\n* May 5 &ndash; [[Danielle Fishel]], actress\n* May 11 &ndash; [[Daniel Ortmeier]], baseball player\n* May 18 [[Adam Green (musician)|Adam Green]] - singer-songwriter\n* May 20 [[Lindsay Taylor]] - basketball player\n* May 21 [[Josh Hamilton]] - baseball player\n* May 22 [[Melissa Gregory]] -  figure skater\n* May 26 [[Anthony Ervin]] swimmer\n* May 31  &ndash; [[Andy Hurley]], musician \n* June 1 &ndash; [[Smush Parker]], basketball player\n* June 7 &ndash; [[Tyler Johnson (baseball)|Tyler Johnson]], baseball player\n* June 12 [[John Gourley]] musician and singer\n* June 16 [[Ben Kweller]] musician\n* June 19 &ndash; [[Melissa McMorrow]], boxer\n* June 21 &ndash; [[Brandon Flowers]], singer-songwriter\n* June 29 [[Joe Johnson (basketball)|Joe Johnson]] basketball player\n* July 1 &ndash; [[Amanda Seales]], comedian, actress, rapper and songwriter\n* July 4 \n** [[Brock Berlin]], American football player\n** [[Will Smith (defensive end)|Will Smith]], American football player (d. [[2016 in the United States|2016]])\n* July 6 &ndash; [[Mike Karney]], American football player\n* July 28 \n** [[Billy Aaron Brown]], actor\n** [[Cole Williams]], actor\n* August 1  Jordan Wall, actor\n* August 4 &ndash; [[Abigail Spencer]], actress\n* August 21 &ndash; [[Winklevoss twins]], internet entrepreneurs and rowers\n* August 24 &ndash; [[Chad Michael Murray]], fashion model, actor and spokesperson\n* September 4 &ndash; [[Beyonc\u00e9]], singer-songwriter<ref>{{cite web |title=Beyonce {{!}} Biography, Songs, Movies, & Facts |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Beyonce |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |accessdate=3 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* September 8 &ndash; [[Jonathan Taylor Thomas]], actor\n* September 16 &ndash; [[Alexis Bledel]], actress and model\n* September 18 Jennifer Tisdale  actress\n* September 25 &ndash; [[Lee Norris]], actor\n* September 26 Serena Williams, tennis player\n* October 5 &ndash; [[Jeanette Antolin]], gymnast<ref>{{cite web |title=USA Gymnastics {{!}} Jeanette Antolin |url=https://usagym.org/pages/athletes/archivedbios/a/jantolin.html |website=usagym.org |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n* October 9 &ndash; [[Zachery Ty Bryan]], actor\n* October 14 &ndash; [[Boof Bonser]], baseball player\n* October 20 Willis McGahee, football player\n* October 29 Amanda Beard swimmer\n* October 30 Chris Clemons, football player\n* [[October 31]] [[Frank Iero]] guitarist (My Chemical Romance)\n* November 13\n** [[Ryan Bertin]], wrestler and coach\n** [[Kirsten Price (actress)|Kirsten Price]], model and adult film star\n** [[Rivkah (artist)|Rivkah]], author and illustrator\n* November 15 &ndash; [[Drew Hodgdon]], American football player\n* November 17 &ndash; [[Doug Walker (actor)|Doug Walker]], Italian-born internet comedian (''Nostalgia Critic'')\n* November 25 &ndash; [[Chevon Troutman]], basketball player\n* December 2 &ndash; [[Britney Spears]], singer, dancer and actress\n* December 11  \n** [[Jeff McComsey]], author and illustrator\n** [[Kevin Phillips (actor)|Kevin Phillips]], actor\n** [[Zacky Vengeance]], guitarist ([[Avenged Sevenfold]])\n* December 12 &ndash; [[Ronnie Brown]], American football player\n* December 13 \n** [[Mathis Bailey]], American-Canadian novelist and fiction writer\n** [[Amy Lee]], singer-songwriter\n* December 16 &ndash; [[Krysten Ritter]], actress, musician, model and author\n* December 20 &ndash; [[Roy Williams (wide receiver)|Roy Williams]], American football player\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Deaths==\n{{see also|Deaths in 1981}}\n* January 5\n** [[Frederick Osborn]], philanthropist and eugenicist (b. [[1889 in the United States|1889]])\n** [[Harold Urey]], winner of the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] (b. [[1893 in the United States|1893]])\n* January 7 &ndash; [[John Pascal]], playwright, screenwriter, author and journalist (b. [[1932 in the United States|1932]])\n* January 8 &ndash; [[Matthew Beard (American actor)|Matthew Beard]], child film actor (b. [[1925 in the United States|1925]])\n* January 10\n** [[Katharine Alexander]], film actress (b. [[1898 in the United States|1898]])\n** [[Richard Boone]], Western film actor (b. [[1917 in the United States|1917]])\n* January 11 &ndash; [[Beulah Bondi]], actress (b. [[1888 in the United States|1888]])\n* January 13 &ndash; [[Robert Kellard]], film actor (b. [[1915 in the United States|1915]])\n* January 25 &ndash; [[Adele Astaire]], dancer (b. [[1896 in the United States|1896]])\n* February 9\n** [[Jack Z. Anderson]], U.S. Representative from California (b. [[1904 in the United States|1904]])\n** [[Bill Haley (musician)|Bill Haley]], rock & roll musician (b. [[1925 in the United States|1925]])\n* February 22 &ndash; [[Ilo Wallace]], wife of [[Henry A. Wallace]], [[Second Lady of the United States]] (born [[1888 in the United States|1888]])\n* March 5 &ndash; [[Yip Harburg]], lyricist (b. [[1896 in the United States|1896]])\n* March 7 &ndash; [[Bosley Crowther]], film critic (b. [[1905 in the United States|1905]])\n* March 9 &ndash; [[Max Delbr\u00fcck]], biologist, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] (b. [[1906 in Germany]])\n* April 7 &ndash; [[Norman Taurog]], film director (b. [[1899 in the United States|1899]])\n* April 8 &ndash; [[Omar N. Bradley]], U.S. Army General (b. [[1893 in the United States|1893]])\n* April 12 &ndash; [[Joe Louis]], African American heavyweight boxer (b. [[1914 in the United States|1914]])\n* April 15 &ndash; [[John Thach]], naval aviator and admiral (b. [[1905 in the United States|1905]])\n* April 26\n** [[Jim Davis (actor)|Jim Davis]], television actor (b. [[1909 in the United States|1909]])\n** [[Madge Evans]], actress (b. 1909)\n* April 27 &ndash; [[John Aspinwall Roosevelt]], businessman and philanthropist (b. [[1916 in the United States|1916]])\n* April 28 &ndash; [[Cliff Battles]], American footballer ([[Boston Redskins]]) (b. [[1910 in the United States|1910]])\n* May 9 &ndash; [[Nelson Algren]], novelist (b. [[1909 in the United States|1909]])\n* May 11 &ndash; [[Bob Marley]], reggae musician (b. [[1945]] in Jamaica)\n* May 18\n** [[Arthur O'Connell]], actor (b. [[1908 in the United States|1908]])\n** [[William Saroyan]], dramatist and author (b. 1908)\n* May 23 &ndash; [[George Jessel (actor)|George Jessel]], actor and entertainer (b. [[1898 in the United States|1898]])\n* May 28 &ndash; [[Mary Lou Williams]], jazz pianist (b. [[1910 in the United States|1910]])\n* July 27\n** [[Murder of Adam Walsh|Adam Walsh]], murder victim and son of [[John Walsh (television host)|John Walsh]] (b. [[1974 in the United States|1974]])\n** [[William Wyler]], film director (b. [[1902 in the United States|1902]])\n* July 29 &ndash; [[Robert Moses]], urban planner (b. [[1888 in the United States|1888]])\n* November 7 &ndash; [[Will Durant]], philosopher and writer (b. [[1885 in the United States|1885]])\n* November 12 &ndash; [[William Holden]], film actor (b. [[1918 in the United States|1918]])\n* November 17 &ndash; [[Sibyl M. Rock]], mathematician (b. [[1909 in the United States|1909]])\n* November 27 &ndash; [[Lotte Lenya]], singer (b. [[1898]] in Vienna)\n* November 29 &ndash; [[Natalie Wood]], actress (b. [[1938 in the United States|1938]])\n* December 2 &ndash; [[Wallace Harrison]], architect (b. [[1895 in the United States|1895]])\n* December 6 &ndash; [[Harry Harlow]], psychologist (b. [[1905 in the United States|1905]])\n* December 7 &ndash; [[Hoagy Carmichael]], composer and singer (b. [[1899 in the United States|1899]])\n* December 13 &ndash; [[Pigmeat Markham]], African American vaudevillian (b. [[1904 in the United States|1904]])\n\n==See also==\n* [[1981 in American television]]\n* [[List of American films of 1981]]\n* [[Timeline of United States history (1970\u20131989)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{US year nav}}\n{{Timeline of United States history}}\n{{North America topic|1981 in}}\n\n[[Category:1981 in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:1981 by country]]\n", "text_old": "{{expand list|date=July 2014}}\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2014}}\n{{Yearbox US|1981}}\nEvents from the year '''1981 in the United States'''.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Incumbents ==\n\n=== Federal government ===\n* [[President of the United States|President]]: [[Jimmy Carter]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]) (until January 20), [[Ronald Reagan]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[California]]) (starting January 20)\n* [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]: [[Walter Mondale]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Minnesota]]) (until January 20), [[George H. W. Bush]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Texas]]) (starting January 20)\n* [[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]]: [[Warren E. Burger]] ([[Minnesota]])\n* [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]]: [[Tip O'Neill]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Massachusetts]])\n* [[Senate Majority Leader]]: [[Robert Byrd]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[West Virginia]]) (until January 3), [[Howard Baker]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Tennessee]]) (starting January 3)\n* [[United States Congress|Congress]]: [[96th United States Congress|96th]] (until January 3), [[97th United States Congress|97th]] (starting January 3)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n! [[Governor (United States)|Governor]]s and [[Lieutenant governor (United States)|lieutenant governor]]s\n|-\n|\n=== Governors ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Governor of Alabama]]: [[Fob James]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Alaska]]: [[Jay Hammond]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Arizona]]: [[Bruce Babbitt]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Arkansas]]: [[Bill Clinton]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 19), [[Frank D. White]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 19)\n* [[Governor of California]]: [[Jerry Brown]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Colorado]]: [[Richard Lamm]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Connecticut]]: [[William O'Neill (Connecticut politician)|William A. O'Neill]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Delaware]]: [[Pierre S. du Pont, IV]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Florida]]: [[Bob Graham]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Georgia]]: [[George Busbee]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Hawaii]]: [[George Ariyoshi]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Idaho]]: [[John V. Evans]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Illinois]]: [[James R. Thompson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Indiana]]: [[Otis R. Bowen]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 12), [[Robert D. Orr]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 12)\n* [[Governor of Iowa]]: [[Robert D. Ray]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Governor of Kansas]]: [[John W. Carlin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Kentucky]]: [[John Y. Brown Jr.]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Louisiana]]: [[David C. Treen]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Maine]]: [[Joseph E. Brennan]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Maryland]]: [[Harry R. Hughes]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Massachusetts]]: [[Edward J. King]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Michigan]]: [[William Milliken]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Minnesota]]: [[Al Quie]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Mississippi]]: [[William Winter (politician)|William Winter]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Missouri]]: [[Joseph P. Teasdale]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 12), [[Kit Bond]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 12)\n* [[Governor of Montana]]: [[Thomas Lee Judge]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 5), [[Ted Schwinden]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 5)\n* [[Governor of Nebraska]]: [[Charles Thone]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Nevada]]: [[Robert List]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of New Hampshire]]: [[Hugh J. Gallen]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of New Jersey]]: [[Brendan Byrne]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])  \n* [[Governor of New Mexico]]: [[Bruce King]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of New York]]: [[Hugh Carey]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of North Carolina]]: [[Jim Hunt]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of North Dakota]]: [[Arthur A. Link]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 6), [[Allen I. Olson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 6) \n* [[Governor of Ohio]]: [[Jim Rhodes]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Oklahoma]]: [[George Nigh]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Governor of Oregon]]: [[Victor G. Atiyeh]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Pennsylvania]]: [[Dick Thornburgh]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])  \n* [[Governor of Rhode Island]]: [[J. Joseph Garrahy]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of South Carolina]]: [[Richard Riley]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of South Dakota]]: [[William J. Janklow]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Tennessee]]: [[Lamar Alexander]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Texas]]: [[Bill Clements]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Utah]]: [[Scott M. Matheson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Vermont]]: [[Richard A. Snelling]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Virginia]]: [[John N. Dalton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Washington]]: [[Dixy Lee Ray]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 14), [[John Spellman]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 14)\n* [[Governor of West Virginia]]: [[Jay Rockefeller]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Wisconsin]]: [[Lee S. Dreyfus]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Wyoming]]: [[Edgar J. Herschler]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n}}\n\n=== Lieutenant governors ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Alabama]]: [[George McMillan (politician)|George McMillan]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Alaska]]: [[Terry Miller (politician)|Terry Miller]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Arkansas]]: [[Joe Purcell]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 19), [[Winston Bryant]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 19)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of California]]: [[Mike Curb]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Colorado]]: [[Nancy E. Dick]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut]]: [[Joseph J. Fauliso]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Delaware]]: [[James D. McGinnis]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 20), [[Michael N. Castle]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 20)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Florida]]: [[Wayne Mixson]]  ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Georgia]]: [[Zell Miller]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Hawaii]]: [[Jean King]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Idaho]]: [[Phil Batt]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Illinois]]: [[Dave O'Neal]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until July 31), vacant (starting July 31)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Indiana]]: [[Robert D. Orr]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 12), [[John Mutz]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 12)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Iowa]]: [[Terry E. Branstad]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Kansas]]: [[Paul V. Dugan]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Kentucky]]: [[Martha Layne Collins]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Louisiana]]: [[Bobby Freeman (politician)|Robert \"Bobby\" Freeman]]  ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Maryland]]: [[Samuel Bogley]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Massachusetts]]: [[Thomas P. O'Neill III]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Michigan]]: [[James H. Brickley]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Minnesota]]: [[Lou Wangberg]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Mississippi]]: [[Brad Dye]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Missouri]]: [[William C. Phelps]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until January 12), [[Kenneth Rothman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 12)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Montana]]: [[Ted Schwinden]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 5), [[George Turman]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 5)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Nebraska]]: [[Roland A. Luedtke]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Nevada]]: [[Myron E. Leavitt]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico]]: [[Roberto Mondrag\u00f3n]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of New York]]: [[Mario Cuomo]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of North Carolina]]: [[James C. Green]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of North Dakota]]: [[Wayne G. Sanstead]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until month and day unknown), [[Ernest Sands]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting month and day unknown)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Ohio]]: vacant\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Oklahoma]]: [[Spencer Bernard (politician)|Spencer Bernard]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Pennsylvania]]: [[William Scranton, III]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Rhode Island]]: [[Thomas R. DiLuglio]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of South Carolina]]: [[Nancy Stevenson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of South Dakota]]: [[Lowell C. Hansen II]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Tennessee]]: [[John S. Wilder]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Texas]]: [[William P. Hobby Jr.]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Utah]]: [[David Smith Monson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Vermont]]: [[Madeleine M. Kunin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Virginia]]: [[Chuck Robb]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Washington]]: [[John Cherberg]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Wisconsin]]: [[Russell A. Olson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n}}\n|}\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n[[File:Official Portrait of President Reagan 1981.jpg|thumb|right|120px|January 20: [[Ronald Reagan]] becomes President]]\n[[File:Iran hostages return.jpg|thumb|right|120px|January 20: The [[Iran hostage crisis]] ends with their release]]\n* January 19 &ndash; United States and [[Iran]]ian officials sign an agreement to release 52 American [[hostage]]s after 14 months of [[Imprisonment|captivity]].\n* January 20 &ndash; [[Ronald Reagan]] is sworn in as the 40th [[President of the United States]]. Minutes later, [[Iran]] releases the 52 Americans held for 444 days, ending the [[Iran hostage crisis]].\n* January 25 &ndash; [[Super Bowl XV]]: The [[Oakland Raiders]] defeat the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] 27\u201310 at the [[Louisiana Superdome]] in [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]].\n\n===February===\n* February 10 &ndash; A fire at the [[Las Vegas Hilton]] [[hotel]]-[[casino]] kills 8 and injures 198.\n\n===March===\n[[File:President Ronald Reagan moments before he was shot in an assassination attempt 1981.jpg|thumb|right|120px|March 30: [[Reagan assassination attempt]]]]\n* March 6 &ndash; After 19 years hosting the ''[[CBS Evening News]]'', [[Walter Cronkite]] signs off for the last time.\n* March 19 &ndash; Three workers are killed and 5 injured during a test of the [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']].\n* March 21 &ndash;  [[Michael Donald]] [[lynched]].\n* March 30 &ndash; U.S. President [[Ronald Reagan]] is [[Reagan assassination attempt|shot in the chest]] outside a [[Washington, D.C.]]  hotel by [[John Hinckley, Jr.]] Two police officers and Press Secretary [[James Brady]] are also wounded.\n* March 31 &ndash; The [[53rd Academy Awards]], hosted by [[Johnny Carson]], are held at the [[Dorothy Chandler Pavilion]] in [[Los Angeles]]. [[Robert Redford]]'s directorial debut in ''[[Ordinary People]]'' wins [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]].\n\n===April===\n[[File:Space Shuttle Columbia launching.jpg|thumb|right|120px|April 12: The first [[STS-1|Space Shuttle]] launch]]\n* April 12 &ndash; The [[Space Shuttle]] program: ''[[Space Shuttle Columbia]]'' ([[Johhhm Young (astronaut)|John Young]], [[Robert Crippen]]) launches on the [[STS-1]] mission, returning to Earth on April 14.\n* April 18 &ndash; A [[Minor League Baseball]] game between the [[Rochester Red Wings]] and the [[Pawtucket Red Sox]] at [[McCoy Stadium]] in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island]], becomes the [[longest professional baseball game]] in history: 8 hours and 25 minutes/33 innings (the 33rd inning is not played until June 23).\n* April 26 &ndash; The 5.9 {{M|w|link=y}} [[List of earthquakes in California|Westmorland earthquake]] shook the [[Imperial Valley]] of California with a maximum [[Mercalli intensity scale|Mercalli intensity]] of VII (''Very strong''), causing $1\u20133 million in damage.\n\n===May===\n* May 15 &ndash; [[Donna Payant]] is murdered by serial killer [[Lemuel Smith]], the first time a female prison officer has been killed on-duty in the United States.\n\n===June===\n* June &ndash; The United States enters the severe [[early 1980s recession]], exactly a year after the more minor 1980 recession ended; the unemployment rate is 7.2%\n* June 5 &ndash; The [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] report that five [[homosexuality|homosexual]] men in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], have a rare form of [[pneumonia]] seen only in patients with weakened [[immune system]]s (the first recognized cases of [[AIDS]]).\n* June 12 &ndash; [[Major League Baseball]] goes on [[1981 Major League Baseball strike|strike]], forcing the cancellation of 38 percent of the schedule.\n* June 21 &ndash; [[Wayne Williams]], a 23-year-old [[African American]], is arrested and charged with the murders of two other [[African Americans]]. He is later accused of 28 others, in the [[Atlanta child murders]].\n* June 29 &ndash; Morris Edwin Robert, armed with a machine gun, holds hostages in the FBI section at the [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] Federal Building. After three hours, the hostages are rescued and Robert is killed in a shootout with federal agents.\n\n===July===\n[[File:Hyatt Regency collapse floor view.PNG|thumb|right|120px|July 17: [[Hyatt Regency walkway collapse]]]]\n* July 7 &ndash; [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] nominates the first woman, [[Sandra Day O'Connor]], to the [[Supreme Court of the United States]].\n* July 8 &ndash; [[California]] Governor [[Jerry Brown]], faced with a [[Mediterranean fruit fly]] infestation, chooses to delay the aerial spraying of [[malathion]], in favor of continuing ground-based eradication efforts.\n* July 9 &ndash; First release of [[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]] and first debut of [[Mario (franchise)|Mario]].\n* July 17 \n**[[Hyatt Regency walkway collapse]]: Two skywalks filled with people at the Hyatt Regency Hotel in [[Kansas City, Missouri]] collapse into a crowded atrium lobby, killing 114.\n**[[Israel]]i aircraft bomb [[Beirut]], [[Lebanese Civil War#Israeli bombing of Beirut|destroying multi-story apartment blocks]] containing the offices of [[PLO]] associated groups, killing approximately 300 civilians and resulting in worldwide condemnation and a U.S. embargo on the export of aircraft to Israel.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Bombing of Beirut|journal=Journal of Palestine Studies|volume=11|issue=1|year=1981|pages=218\u2013225|doi=10.1525/jps.1981.11.1.00p0366x}}</ref>\n* July 27 &ndash; [[Murder of Adam Walsh|Adam Walsh]], 6, is kidnapped from a Sears store in Hollywood, Florida.\n\n===August===\n* August 1 &ndash; [[MTV]] (Music Television) is launched on cable television in the United States.\n* August 5 &ndash; U.S. President [[Ronald Reagan]] fires 11,359 [[Strike action|striking]] [[air-traffic controller]]s who ignored his order for them to return to work.\n* August 7 &ndash; ''The [[Washington Star]]'' ceases publication after 128 years.\n* August 9 &ndash; [[Major League Baseball]] resumes from [[1981 Major League Baseball strike|the strike]] with the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]]'s [[Cleveland Stadium|Municipal Stadium]].\n* August 10 &ndash; Exactly two weeks after his disappearance, the severed head of 6-year-old [[Hollywood, Florida]] native [[Murder of Adam Walsh|Adam Walsh]] is found in a canal in [[Vero Beach, Florida]]; to this day the rest of the boy's body has never been recovered.\n* August 12 &ndash; The original Model 5150 [[IBM PC]] (with a 4.77&nbsp;MHz [[Intel 8088]] processor) is released in the United States at a base price of $1,565.\n* August 19 \n**[[Gulf of Sidra incident (1981)]]: [[Libya]]n leader [[Muammar al-Gaddafi]] sends 2 [[Sukhoi Su-22]] fighter jets to intercept 2 U.S. fighters over the [[Gulf of Sidra]]. The American jets destroy the Libyan fighters.\n**U.S. President [[Ronald Reagan]] appoints the first female U.S. Supreme Court Justice, [[Sandra Day O'Connor]].\n* August 24 &ndash; [[Mark David Chapman]] is sentenced to 20 years to life in prison, after being convicted of murdering [[John Lennon]] in [[Manhattan]] eight months earlier.\n* August 31 &ndash; A bomb explodes at the [[Ramstein Air Base|U.S. Air Force base in Ramstein]], [[West Germany]], injuring 20 people.\n\n===September===\n* September 10 &ndash; [[Picasso]]'s painting \"[[Guernica (painting)|Guernica]]\" is moved from [[New York City]] to [[Madrid]].\n* September 11 &ndash; A small plane crashes into the [[Swing Auditorium]] in [[San Bernardino, California]], damaging the venue beyond repair.\n* September 15 &ndash; The ''[[John Bull (locomotive)|John Bull]]'' becomes the oldest operable [[steam locomotive]] in the world, at 150 years old, when it operates under its own power outside [[Washington, DC]].\n* September 17 &ndash; [[Ric Flair]] defeats Dusty Rhodes to win his first World Heavyweight Wrestling Championship in [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]].\n* September 19 &ndash; [[Simon & Garfunkel]] perform [[The Concert in Central Park]], a free concert in New York in front of approximately half a million people.\n* September 25 \n**[[Sandra Day O'Connor]] takes her seat as the first female justice of the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].\n**[[The Rolling Stones]] begin their [[Tattoo You]] tour at [[JFK Stadium]] in [[Philadelphia]].\n\n===October===\n* October 28 &ndash; The [[Thrash metal music|thrash metal]] band [[Metallica]] forms in [[Los Angeles]].\n** The [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] defeat the [[New York Yankees]], 4 games to 2, to win their 5th World Series Title.\n\n===November===\n* November 12 &ndash; [[STS-2]]: [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']] ([[Joe Engle]], [[Richard Truly]]) lifts off for its second mission.\n* November 16 &ndash; Luke and Laura marry on the U.S. soap opera ''[[General Hospital]]''; it is the highest-rated hour in daytime television history.\n* November 23 &ndash; [[Iran-Contra scandal]]: [[Ronald Reagan]] signs the [[Classified information|top secret]] National Security Decision Directive 17 (NSDD-17), authorizing the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] to recruit and support [[Contras|Contra]] rebels in [[Nicaragua]].\n* November 30 &ndash; [[Cold War]]: In [[Geneva]], representatives from the United States and the [[Soviet Union]] begin negotiating intermediate-range [[nuclear weapon]] reductions in [[Europe]] (the meetings end inconclusively on Thursday, December 17).\n\n===December===\n\n* December 5 &ndash; American general [[James L. Dozier]] is kidnapped in [[Verona]] by the Italian [[Red Brigades]].\n* December 8 &ndash; The [[No. 21 Mine explosion]] in [[Whitwell, Tennessee]] kills 13.\n* December 11 &ndash; [[Boxing]]: [[Muhammad Ali]] loses to [[Trevor Berbick]]; this proved to be Ali's last-ever fight.\n* December 28 &ndash; The first American [[test-tube baby]], [[Elizabeth Jordan Carr]], is born in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].\n\n===Ongoing===\n* [[Cold War]] (1947\u20131991)\n* [[Iran hostage crisis]] (1979\u20131981)\n* [[Early 1980s recession]] (1981\u20131982)\n\n==Births==\n{{Div col