actor\n* October 14 &ndash; [[Boof Bonser]], baseball player\n* October 20 Willis McGahee, football player\n* October 29 Amanda Beard swimmer\n* October 30 Chris Clemons, football player\n* [[October 31]] [[Frank Iero]] guitarist (My Chemical Romance)\n* November 13\n** [[Ryan Bertin]], wrestler and coach\n** [[Kirsten Price (actress)|Kirsten Price]], model and adult film star\n** [[Rivkah (artist)|Rivkah]], author and illustrator\n* November 15 &ndash; [[Drew Hodgdon]], American football player\n* November 17 &ndash; [[Doug Walker (actor)|Doug Walker]], Italian-born internet comedian (''Nostalgia Critic'')\n* November 25 &ndash; [[Chevon Troutman]], basketball player\n* December 2 &ndash; [[Britney Spears]], singer, dancer and actress\n* December 11  \n** [[Jeff McComsey]], author and illustrator\n** [[Kevin Phillips (actor)|Kevin Phillips]], actor\n** [[Zacky Vengeance]], guitarist ([[Avenged Sevenfold]])\n* December 12 &ndash; [[Ronnie Brown]], American football player\n* December 13 \n** [[Mathis Bailey]], American-Canadian novelist and fiction writer\n** [[Amy Lee]], singer-songwriter\n* December 16 &ndash; [[Krysten Ritter]], actress, musician, model and author\n* December 20 &ndash; [[Roy Williams (wide receiver)|Roy Williams]], American football player\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Deaths==\n{{see also|Deaths in 1981}}\n* January 5\n** [[Frederick Osborn]], philanthropist and eugenicist (b. [[1889 in the United States|1889]])\n** [[Harold Urey]], winner of the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] (b. [[1893 in the United States|1893]])\n* January 7 &ndash; [[John Pascal]], playwright, screenwriter, author and journalist (b. [[1932 in the United States|1932]])\n* January 8 &ndash; [[Matthew Beard (American actor)|Matthew Beard]], child film actor (b. [[1925 in the United States|1925]])\n* January 10\n** [[Katharine Alexander]], film actress (b. [[1898 in the United States|1898]])\n** [[Richard Boone]], Western film actor (b. [[1917 in the United States|1917]])\n* January 11 &ndash; [[Beulah Bondi]], actress (b. [[1888 in the United States|1888]])\n* January 13 &ndash; [[Robert Kellard]], film actor (b. [[1915 in the United States|1915]])\n* January 25 &ndash; [[Adele Astaire]], dancer (b. [[1896 in the United States|1896]])\n* February 9\n** [[Jack Z. Anderson]], U.S. Representative from California (b. [[1904 in the United States|1904]])\n** [[Bill Haley (musician)|Bill Haley]], rock & roll musician (b. [[1925 in the United States|1925]])\n* February 22 &ndash; [[Ilo Wallace]], wife of [[Henry A. Wallace]], [[Second Lady of the United States]] (born [[1888 in the United States|1888]])\n* March 5 &ndash; [[Yip Harburg]], lyricist (b. [[1896 in the United States|1896]])\n* March 7 &ndash; [[Bosley Crowther]], film critic (b. [[1905 in the United States|1905]])\n* March 9 &ndash; [[Max Delbr\u00fcck]], biologist, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] (b. [[1906 in Germany]])\n* April 7 &ndash; [[Norman Taurog]], film director (b. [[1899 in the United States|1899]])\n* April 8 &ndash; [[Omar N. Bradley]], U.S. Army General (b. [[1893 in the United States|1893]])\n* April 12 &ndash; [[Joe Louis]], African American heavyweight boxer (b. [[1914 in the United States|1914]])\n* April 15 &ndash; [[John Thach]], naval aviator and admiral (b. [[1905 in the United States|1905]])\n* April 26\n** [[Jim Davis (actor)|Jim Davis]], television actor (b. [[1909 in the United States|1909]])\n** [[Madge Evans]], actress (b. 1909)\n* April 27 &ndash; [[John Aspinwall Roosevelt]], businessman and philanthropist (b. [[1916 in the United States|1916]])\n* April 28 &ndash; [[Cliff Battles]], American footballer ([[Boston Redskins]]) (b. [[1910 in the United States|1910]])\n* May 9 &ndash; [[Nelson Algren]], novelist (b. [[1909 in the United States|1909]])\n* May 11 &ndash; [[Bob Marley]], reggae musician (b. [[1945]] in Jamaica)\n* May 18\n** [[Arthur O'Connell]], actor (b. [[1908 in the United States|1908]])\n** [[William Saroyan]], dramatist and author (b. 1908)\n* May 23 &ndash; [[George Jessel (actor)|George Jessel]], actor and entertainer (b. [[1898 in the United States|1898]])\n* May 28 &ndash; [[Mary Lou Williams]], jazz pianist (b. [[1910 in the United States|1910]])\n* July 27\n** [[Murder of Adam Walsh|Adam Walsh]], murder victim and son of [[John Walsh (television host)|John Walsh]] (b. [[1974 in the United States|1974]])\n** [[William Wyler]], film director (b. [[1902 in the United States|1902]])\n* July 29 &ndash; [[Robert Moses]], urban planner (b. [[1888 in the United States|1888]])\n* November 7 &ndash; [[Will Durant]], philosopher and writer (b. [[1885 in the United States|1885]])\n* November 12 &ndash; [[William Holden]], film actor (b. [[1918 in the United States|1918]])\n* November 17 &ndash; [[Sibyl M. Rock]], mathematician (b. [[1909 in the United States|1909]])\n* November 27 &ndash; [[Lotte Lenya]], singer (b. [[1898]] in Vienna)\n* November 29 &ndash; [[Natalie Wood]], actress (b. [[1938 in the United States|1938]])\n* December 2 &ndash; [[Wallace Harrison]], architect (b. [[1895 in the United States|1895]])\n* December 6 &ndash; [[Harry Harlow]], psychologist (b. [[1905 in the United States|1905]])\n* December 7 &ndash; [[Hoagy Carmichael]], composer and singer (b. [[1899 in the United States|1899]])\n* December 13 &ndash; [[Pigmeat Markham]], African American vaudevillian (b. [[1904 in the United States|1904]])\n\n==See also==\n* [[1981 in American television]]\n* [[List of American films of 1981]]\n* [[Timeline of United States history (1970\u20131989)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{US year nav}}\n{{Timeline of United States history}}\n{{North America topic|1981 in}}\n\n[[Category:1981 in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:1981 by country]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 2 links to disambiguation pages -(You can help)-Adam Green,Joe Johnson", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1981_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "List of Marvel Cinematic Universe television series", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use list-defined references|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| italic_title         = no\n| show_name            = {{noitalic|Marvel Cinematic Universe television series}}\n| image                = \n| alt                  = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = \n| format               =\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = {{Based on|Characters published|[[Marvel Comics]]}}\n| starring             = \n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = {{#expr:\n {{tmpv|Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.|Infobox television||num_seasons}} +\n {{tmpv|Agent Carter (TV series)|Infobox television||num_seasons}} +\n {{tmpv|Daredevil (TV series)|Infobox television||num_seasons}} +\n {{tmpv|Jessica Jones (TV series)|Infobox television||num_seasons}} +\n {{tmpv|Luke Cage (TV series)|Infobox television||num_seasons}} +\n {{tmpv|Iron Fist (TV series)|Infobox television||num_seasons}} +\n {{tmpv|The Defenders (miniseries)|Infobox television||num_seasons}} +\n {{tmpv|Inhumans (TV series)|Infobox television||num_seasons}} +\n {{tmpv|The Punisher (TV series)|Infobox television||num_seasons}} +\n {{tmpv|Runaways (TV series)|Infobox television||num_seasons}} +\n {{tmpv|Cloak & Dagger (TV series)|Infobox television||num_seasons}}\n}} (across 11 series)\n| num_episodes         = {{#expr:\n {{tmpv|Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.|Infobox television||num_episodes}} +\n {{tmpv|Agent Carter (TV series)|Infobox television||num_episodes}} +\n {{tmpv|Daredevil (TV series)|Infobox television||num_episodes}} +\n {{tmpv|Jessica Jones (TV series)|Infobox television||num_episodes}} +\n {{tmpv|Luke Cage (TV series)|Infobox television||num_episodes}} +\n {{tmpv|Iron Fist (TV series)|Infobox television||num_episodes}} +\n {{tmpv|The Defenders (miniseries)|Infobox television||num_episodes}} +\n {{tmpv|Inhumans (TV series)|Infobox television||num_episodes}} +\n {{tmpv|The Punisher (TV series)|Infobox television||num_episodes}} +\n {{tmpv|Runaways (TV series)|Infobox television||num_episodes}} +\n {{tmpv|Cloak & Dagger (TV series)|Infobox television||num_episodes}}\n}}\n| list_episodes        = \n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* '''Marvel Television'''\n* [[Alan Fine (executive)|Alan Fine]]\n* [[Stan Lee]]\n* [[Joe Quesada]]\n* Jim Chory\n* [[Jeph Loeb]]\n* '''Marvel Studios'''\n* [[Kevin Feige]]\n}}\n| producer             = \n| editor               = \n| location             =\n| cinematography       = \n| camera               =\n| runtime              = \n| company              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Marvel Television]]\n* [[Marvel Studios]]\n}}\n| distributor          = \n| network              = {{Plainlist|\n* '''Marvel Television'''\n* [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n* [[Netflix]]\n* [[Hulu]]\n* [[Freeform (TV channel)|Freeform]]\n* '''Marvel Studios'''\n* [[Disney+]]\n}}\n| picture_format       = \n| audio_format         = \n| first_aired          = {{nowrap|{{Start date|2013|9|24}}}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|present}}\n| preceded_by          =\n| followed_by          =\n| related              =\n| website              = \n| website_title        = \n| production_website   =\n}}\nThe [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] (MCU) television series are American superhero television shows based on characters that appear in publications by [[Marvel Comics]]. They are set in, or inspired by, the [[shared universe]] of the [[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe films|MCU film franchise]].\n\nThe MCU first expanded to television after the creation of [[Marvel Television]] in 2010, with that studio producing 12 series alongside [[ABC Studios]] and its production division [[ABC Studios#ABC Signature|ABC Signature Studios]]. These premiered across broadcast, streaming, and cable television on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[Netflix]] and [[Hulu]], and [[Freeform (TV channel)|Freeform]], respectively. The main ABC series were inspired by the films and featured film characters, and were referred to as the \"Marvel Heroes\" series. A connected group of series for Netflix were called the \"Marvel Knights\" series, and crossed over with each other. [[Young adult fiction|Young adult]]-focused series were produced for Freeform and Hulu, while the latter also had a group of series called \"Adventure into Fear\" planned before Marvel Television was shut down in December 2019.\n\n[[Marvel Studios]]\u2014the production studio behind the films\u2014began producing their own series for the streaming service [[Disney+]] in 2018, with at least eight series in development. These are focused on supporting characters from the films, have much larger budgets than Marvel Television series, and interconnect with the films in a way that the Marvel Television series did not. Following the end of Marvel Television's series on ABC, that network expressed interest in working with Marvel Studios to produce future broadcast Marvel series.\n\n==Development==\nIn June 2010, [[Marvel Television]] was launched with [[Jeph Loeb]] as head.<ref name=\"TVLaunch\" /> The studio began producing television series inspired by the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film franchise,<ref name=\"DeadlineSHIELDPilot\" /><ref name=\"AtwellAgentCarterTV\"/> though it had to be aware of [[Marvel Studios]]' plans for the films so as not to interfere when introducing someone or something to the universe.<ref name=\"AoSProducersTHR\" /> [[Joss Whedon]], who directed ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]'' (2012) for Marvel Studios before co-creating ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'' for Marvel Television, described the relationship between the MCU television series and films as the series getting \"leftovers\" from the films.<ref name=\"JossScepter\" /> In August 2015, Marvel Studios was integrated into [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|The Walt Disney Studios]] with President [[Kevin Feige]] reporting to Walt Disney Studios chairman [[Alan F. Horn|Alan Horn]] instead of Marvel Entertainment CEO [[Isaac Perlmutter]], while Marvel Television remained under Perlmutter's control.<ref name=\"MarvelDisneyAug2015\" /> This was seen as widening the existing divide between the Marvel film and television divisions, and making it even less likely that the films would acknowledge the series' events and characters.<ref name=\"MarvelDisneyAug2015/Film\" />\n\nBy September 2018, Marvel was developing several limited series for Disney's new streaming service [[Disney+]], to be centered on characters from the MCU films. The series would be produced by Marvel Studios rather than Marvel Television, with Feige taking a \"hands-on role\" in each series' development,<ref name=\"Disney+SeriesSep2018\" /> focusing on \"continuity of story\" with the films and \"handling\" the actors who would be reprising their roles from the films.<ref name=\"FalconWinterSoldier2\" /> Loeb stated that Marvel Television would continue to develop new MCU series, including their own Disney+ series.<ref name=\"LoebAug2019\" /> By September 2019, many of Marvel Television's existing series were cancelled or ending, and several developing projects did not move forward. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that the industry perception of these events was that Marvel Television was being phased out in favor of the new Marvel Studios series, which had access to well-known MCU characters and much larger budgets than Marvel Television series ever had.<ref name=\"MarvelTVUnclear\" /> A month later, Feige was named Chief Creative Officer of Marvel Entertainment, with Marvel Television moving under Marvel Studios and executives of Marvel Television reporting to Feige.<ref name=\"Oct2019Restructure\" /> At the end of October, Loeb was expected to leave Marvel by the end of the year.<ref name=\"LoebGone\" />\n\nIn December, Feige referred to the Marvel Studios series as \"a new type of cinematic [story] that we haven't done before\", and indicated that he considered them the first MCU stories on television by saying \"for the first time ... the MCU will be on your TV screen at home on Disney+ and interconnect with the movies and go back and forth\".<ref name=\"FeigeInterconnectDec2019\" /> The next day, Marvel Television announced that it would complete work on its existing television series but would stop developing new projects. The division was set to shut down, with several executives moving to Marvel Studios to oversee the completion of existing series. Other staff were laid off, while Loeb was set to remain with the company for the handover.<ref name=\"MarvelTVFolded\" /><ref name=\"MarvelTVFolded2\" />\n\n== Marvel Television==\n=== ABC series ===\n{{Main|Marvel's ABC television series}}\n{{#section:Marvel's ABC television series|TVSeriesTable}}\nThe first television series that Marvel Television developed to be part of the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] was ''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.''; it was ordered to pilot by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] in August 2012.<ref name=\"DeadlineSHIELDPilot\" /><ref name=\"Apr2013ABCAllAccess\" /> In January 2014, the series ''[[Agent Carter (TV series)|Agent Carter]]'' was announced, joining ''S.H.I.E.L.D.'' at ABC;<ref name=\"AtwellAgentCarterTV\"/> it was canceled in May 2016.<ref name=\"ACCanceled\" /> In November 2016, Marvel and [[IMAX Corporation]] announced ''[[Inhumans (TV series)|Inhumans]]'', based on the species [[Inhumans|of the same name]], after a planned film based on the characters had been removed from Marvel Studios' slate.<ref name=\"InhumansAnnouncement\" /><ref name=\"InhumansAnnouncement2\" /><ref name=\"InhumansNoThe\" /> ABC canceled the series in May 2018.<ref name=\"InhumansCanceled\" /> In July 2019, it was announced that the seventh season of ''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.'' would be its last.<ref name=\"AoSS7Final\" /> Discussing Marvel Television's wider slate of series in August 2019, Loeb explained that Marvel categorized its ABC series as the \"Marvel Heroes\" series due to their close connections to the MCU films, especially with the main characters of both ''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.'' and ''Agent Carter'' having originated in films before transitioning to their television series.<ref name=\"LoebAug2019\" />\n\n=== Netflix series ===\n{{Main|Marvel's Netflix television series}}\n{{#section:Marvel's Netflix television series|TVSeriesTable}}\nBy October 2013, Marvel was preparing four drama series and a miniseries to present to [[video on demand]] services and cable providers, with [[Netflix]], [[Amazon Instant Video|Amazon]], and [[WGN America]] expressing interest.<ref name=\"DeadlineTVOct2013\" /> That November, it was announced that Disney would provide Netflix with live-action series based on [[Daredevil (Marvel Comics character)|Daredevil]], [[Jessica Jones]], [[Iron Fist (comics)|Iron Fist]], and [[Luke Cage]], leading up to a miniseries based on the [[Defenders (comics)|Defenders]].<ref name=\"DeadlineTVNov2013\" /> In April 2016, Marvel and Netflix ordered ''[[The Punisher (TV series)|The Punisher]]'' as a spin-off from ''[[Daredevil (TV series)|Daredevil]]''.<ref name=\"PunisherEWApr2016\" /> Netflix had canceled all of their Marvel series by the end of February 2019, ending their partnership with Marvel Television but continuing to stream the existing seasons.<ref name=\"JJPunisherCanceled\" /> Loeb stated in August 2019 that when categorizing Marvel Television's wider slate, the Netflix series are referred to internally as the \"Marvel Street-Level Heroes\" or \"[[Marvel Knights]]\".<ref name=\"LoebAug2019\" />\n\n=== Young adult series ===\n{{Main|Marvel's young adult television series}}\n{{#section:Marvel's young adult television series|TVSeriesTable}}\nAt [[San Diego Comic-Con]] 2011, Loeb announced a series based on the [[Marvel Comics]] characters [[Cloak and Dagger (comics)|Cloak and Dagger]] was in development at [[ABC Family]];<ref name=\"ABCFamilyDevelopment\" /> the network\u2014now named [[Freeform (TV channel)|Freeform]]\u2014ordered the project to series in April 2016.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\" /> That August, [[Hulu]] ordered a new series based on the comics group the [[Runaways (comics)|Runaways]].<ref name=\"RunawaysHulu2\" /><ref name=\"RunawaysSeriesOrder\" /> Marvel initially said there were no plans to crossover these series,<ref name=\"TCAJul2017THR\" /> but Cloak and Dagger were announced to be appearing in the third season of ''[[Runaways (TV series)|Runaways]]'' in August 2019.<ref name=\"RunawaysC&DCrossover\" /> Loeb explained that Marvel categorized ''Runaways'' and ''[[Cloak & Dagger (TV series)|Cloak & Dagger]]'' as its \"YA\", or \"[[Young adult fiction|young adult]]\", franchise, and added that Marvel Television's push into the young adult genre was in response to [[Marvel Studios]] doing the same with [[Spider-Man]]. Loeb hoped there would be further crossovers between the two series,<ref name=\"LoebAug2019\" /> but ''Cloak and Dagger'' was canceled in October 2019,<ref name=\"CDCanceled\" /> followed by ''Runaways'' that November.<ref name=\"RunawaysCanceled\" />\n\n=== Adventure into Fear ===\n{{Main|Adventure into Fear (planned franchise)}}\n{{#section:Adventure into Fear (planned franchise)|TVSeriesTable}}\nHulu ordered two series based on [[Ghost Rider]] and the siblings [[Daimon Hellstrom|Daimon]] and [[Satana (Marvel Comics)|Ana Helstrom]] straight-to-series in May 2019. The intention was to build an interconnected universe between the two series in a similar fashion to Marvel's Netflix shows.<ref name=\"GRHSeriesOrderTHR\" /> Marvel initially referred to the series as the cornerstone of the \"Spirits of Vengeance\", with Loeb adding that they were moving into a new, \"chilling\" corner of the Marvel Universe.<ref name=\"GRHSeriesOrderMarvel\" /> Loeb said in August that Marvel was now referring to these series collectively as \"Adventure into Fear\", and that more series under the banner were in development.<ref name=\"LoebAug2019\" /> A month later, Hulu decided to no longer move forward with ''Ghost Rider'' due to creative differences.<ref name=\"GRCanceled\" /> When Marvel Television was folded into Marvel Studios in December, the studio said that production on ''Helstrom'' would be completed but no further series would be developed.<ref name=\"MarvelTVFolded\" />\n\n== Marvel Studios ==\n=== Phase Four ===\n{{Main|Marvel Cinematic Universe: Phase Four#Television series}}\n{{#section:Marvel Cinematic Universe: Phase Four|TVSeriesTable}}\nBy September 2018, Marvel Studios was developing several limited series centered on \"second tier\" characters from the MCU films who had not and were unlikely to star in their own films; the actors who portrayed the characters in the films reprise their roles for the limited series.<ref name=\"Disney+SeriesSep2018\" /> In March 2019, Feige said the series would take characters from the films, change them, and see those changes reflected in future films; new characters introduced in the series could also go on to appear in films.<ref name=\"FeigeConnectedMar2019\" /> During the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]], Feige announced ''The Falcon and the Winter Soldier'', ''WandaVision'', ''Loki'', ''What If...?'', and ''Hawkeye'' as part of Marvel Studios' [[Marvel Cinematic Universe: Phase Four|Phase Four]] slate alongside several films.<ref name=\"THRPhase4SDCC\" /> At [[D23 Expo]] 2019, Feige announced ''Ms. Marvel'', ''Moon Knight'', and ''She-Hulk'' as also part of Phase Four.<ref name=\"D23Phase4\" /> The series budgets are reportedly $100\u2013150 million each.<ref name=\"MarvelStudiosBudgets\" />\n\n=== Potential ABC series ===\nAfter the shut down of Marvel Television, ABC said that it remained committed to featuring Marvel content.<ref name=\"MarvelTVFolded\" /> In January 2020, ABC Entertainment president Karey Burke said that talks were beginning with Feige and Marvel Studios about what a Marvel Studios series on ABC would be, but she noted that Marvel's focus was on the Disney+ series.<ref name=\"MarvelStudiosABC\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe television series actors]]\n* [[List of television series based on Marvel Comics publications]]\n* [[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe films]]\n* [[Outline of the Marvel Cinematic Universe#Television series|Outline of the Marvel Cinematic Universe]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<!-- DEVELOPMENT -->\n\n<ref name=\"TVLaunch\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2010/06/marvel-entertainment-launches-tv-division-50150/ |title=Marvel Entertainment Launches TV Division |last=Andreeva |first=Natalie |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=June 28, 2010 |accessdate=January 9, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6eOgiRLif?url=http://deadline.com/2010/06/marvel-entertainment-launches-tv-division-50150/ |archivedate=January 9, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DeadlineSHIELDPilot\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/08/abc-greenlights-s-h-i-e-l-d-marvel-pilot-joss-whedon-to-co-write-possibly-direct/ |title=ABC Greenlights 'S.H.I.E.L.D' Marvel Pilot, Joss Whedon To Co-Write & Possibly Direct |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 28, 2012 |accessdate=August 28, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AHlRjwro?url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/08/abc-greenlights-s-h-i-e-l-d-marvel-pilot-joss-whedon-to-co-write-possibly-direct/ |archivedate=August 29, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AtwellAgentCarterTV\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/marvels-agent-carter-hayley-atwell-671839 |title=Marvel's 'Agent Carter': Hayley Atwell, Writers, Showrunners Confirmed for ABC Drama |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |wo