ort]]\n[[Category:1997 in English sport]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions hosted by England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Amateur snooker championship, held 1996 and 1997}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox individual snooker tournament\n|tournament_name=[[World Women's Snooker Championship|Women's World Snooker Championship]]\n|logo=\n|caption=\n|dates= \n|venue= Raunds Cue Sports Club and Terry Griffiths Matchroom\n|location= [[Northamptonshire]] and [[Llanelli]]\n|country= [[United Kingdom]]\n|organisation= [[World Ladies Billiards and Snooker Association]]\n|format= [[Single elimination]]\n|Total prize fund=\n|winners_share= \n|highest_break=87 ([[Karen Corr]])\n|winner=[[Karen Corr]]\n|runner_up=[[Kelly Fisher]]\n|score= 6\u20133\n|previous= [[1995 World Women's Snooker Championship|1995]]\n|next= [[1998 World Women's Snooker Championship|1998]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1997 [[World Women's Snooker Championship]]''' was a women's [[snooker]] tournament held in 1997.\n\n==Tournament summary==\nThe tournament started as the 1996 [[World Women's Snooker Championship|World Championship]], but due to delays in the scheduling of the later rounds, it became the 1997 Championship. It was promoted by [[Barry Hearn]]<ref name=WTOH /> who had been promoting the Women's world championship since [[1990 Women's World Snooker Championship|1990]].<ref name=LATE /> The defending champion was [[Karen Corr]]. There were 52 players who entered the tournament. [[Allison Fisher]] who had won the title seven times, most recently in 1994, did not enter as she has moved to the [[United States]] where she had embarked on a successful [[pool (sports)|pool]] career. 1984 amateur champion and five-times runner-up [[Stacey Hillyard]] had retired from competition and so was another non-participant. The original schedule was for the quarter-finals onwards to be held in [[India]], as they had been in 1994 and 1995,<ref name=LATE /> from 16 to 19 September 1996,<ref name=MTPI /> but eventually the final rounds took place in [[Llanelli]], with the semi-finals and final not happening until well into 1997.\n\nThis was the last women's world snooker championship to be held before the [[World Ladies Billiards and Snooker Association]] amalgamated with the [[WPBSA]] later in 1997.<ref name=YSSP>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->  |date=24 October 1997 |title=Young Stevens silences Parrott  |work=The Guardian |page=B11 |via=ProQuest Historical Newspapers: The Guardian and The Observer. Retrieved 6 December 2019.}}</ref>\n\n===Rounds 1 to 4===\nThe tournament started as the 1996 World Championship. The first four rounds took place at Raunds Cue Sports Club, [[Northamptonshire]], to decide the eight players that would go on to contest the quarter-finals onwards, which were expected to be played in Bombay in mid-September 1996. Defending champion [[Karen Corr]] won her first match without losing a {{cuegloss|frame}} but won only on the final black in the deciding frame of her match against [[Lynette Horsburgh]]. Second seed [[Kelly Fisher]] and 1995 runner-up [[Kim Shaw (snooker player)|Kim Shaw]] both won both of their matches 4\u20130. Mary Talbot, ranked 26th, was a surprising quarter-finalist, beating 7th seed Sarah Smith and 12th ranked player Helen Audus. The highest break in the main qualifying was a 77 by [[Ann-Marie Farren]]. A plate competition was held for players who did not qualify to the quarter finals and was won by Horsburgh, who made a break of 100 in the first round of the plate competition.<ref name=MTPI>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Mary Talbot's passage to India |magazine=Snooker Scene |page=14 |publisher=Everton's News Agency |issue=September 1996}}</ref>\n\n===Quarter-finals===\nFollowing postponements of the final stages and a lack of response from promoter Barry Hearn's partner in India, it was decided to hold the quarter-finals at the Terry Griffiths Matchroom, [[Llanelli]], and they took place in November 1996. Corr [[whitewash (sport)|whitewashed]] 1984 professional champion [[Mandy Fisher]] 4\u20130. Banks saw off 1987 champion Farren 4\u20132, and Lisa Quick beat Shaw 4\u20131. Fisher's match with Talbot was delayed due to Talbot's illness, with Fisher winning 4\u20131. Meanwhile, Hearn requested the termination of his contract with the [[WLBSA]] to promote the event in future.<ref name=WTOH>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=World title on hold |magazine=Snooker Scene |page=37 |publisher=Everton's News Agency |issue=December 1996}}</ref>\n\n===Semi-finals and Final===\nThe semi-finals and final were eventually scheduled to be held in Llanelli in mid-1997, following a continued lack of communication from Hearn's partner in India. Corr made the highest break of the competition, 87, and three other breaks over 30 in overcoming Banks 5\u20130. Quick won the first frame against Fisher, but no more, losing 1\u20135. The final between Corr and Fisher was closely contested until 3\u20133 but then Corr won three frames in a row to take her third world title. The tournament finished some eleven months after the start of the qualifying matches, and was the end of promoter Hearn's relationship with women's snooker that stretched back to 1990.<ref name=LATE>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Karen Corr wins 1996 world title a little late |magazine=Snooker Scene |pages=12\u201313 |publisher=Everton's News Agency |issue=July 1997}}</ref> \n\nThis was the last world championship to be held before the amalgamation of the [[World Ladies Billiards and Snooker Association]] with the [[WPBSA]] a few months later. The intention was that major finals for women should be played at the same venues as the men's events, for example the womens' world championship final being held at the [[Crucible Theatre]] during the [[World Snooker Championship]].<ref name=YSSP />\n\n==Results==\nSource: Snooker Scene<ref name=WTOH /><ref name=LATE /><ref name=MTPI />\n===First round===\nAt Raunds Cue Sports Club. Matches were best-of-7 frames. \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n!  !! Score !! \n|-\n|! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 12em;\" | {{flagicon|SCO}} '''[[Lynette Horsburgh]]''' || align=\"center\"|'''4'''\u20132 ||! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 12em;\"| Zena Latcham {{flagicon|ENG}}\n|-\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} '''[[Kathy Parashis]]''' || align=\"center\"|'''4'''\u20131 || Valerie Finnie {{flagicon|SCO}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} '''Clare Rodgers''' || align=\"center\"|'''4'''\u20130 || Vicki Revell {{flagicon|ENG}}\n|-\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} '''Natalie Chatfield''' || align=\"center\"|'''4'''\u20130 || Jane O'Neill {{flagicon|ENG}}\n|}\n\n===Second round to Final===\n\n{{48TeamBracket\n| RD1='''Second round'''<br>Best-of-7 frames<br>Raunds Cue Sports Club\n| RD2='''Third round'''<br>Best-of-7 frames<br>Raunds Cue Sports Club\n| RD3='''Fourth round'''<br>Best-of-7 frames<br>Raunds Cue Sports Club\n| RD4='''Quarter-finals'''<br>Best-of-7 frames<br>Terry Griffiths Matchroom\n| RD5='''Semi-finals'''<br>Best-of-9 frames<br>Terry Griffiths Matchroom\n| RD6='''Final'''<br>Best-of-11 frames<br>Terry Griffiths Matchroom\n\n| group1=\n| group2=\n| group3=\n| group4=\n\n| seed-width=\n| team-width=\n| score-width=\n\n| RD1-seed01={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team01='''Maureen Twomey'''\n| RD1-score01='''4'''\n| RD1-seed02={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team02=Mary Hawkes\n| RD1-score02=2\n\n| RD1-seed03={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team03=Beverley Hipwell\n| RD1-score03=0\n| RD1-seed04={{flagicon|SCO}}\n| RD1-team04='''Lynette Horsburgh'''\n| RD1-score04='''4'''\n\n| RD1-seed05={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team05='''Sue Parrish'''\n| RD1-score05='''4'''\n| RD1-seed06={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team06=[[Lisa Ingall]]\n| RD1-score06=2\n\n| RD1-seed07={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team07='''Jan Hughes'''\n| RD1-score07='''4'''\n| RD1-seed08={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team08=Marianne Lazarides\n| RD1-score08=1\n\n| RD1-seed09={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team09='''Sherron Audus'''\n| RD1-score09='''4'''\n| RD1-seed10={{flagicon|IRE}}\n| RD1-team10=Greta Browne\n| RD1-score10=3\n\n| RD1-seed11={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team11='''Dawn Wells'''\n| RD1-score11='''4'''\n| RD1-seed12={{flagicon|SCO}}\n| RD1-team12=Jackie Stewart\n| RD1-score12=0\n\n| RD1-seed13={{flagicon|BEL}}\n| RD1-team13=Valerie Van Bellinghen\n| RD1-score13=0\n| RD1-seed14={{flagicon|AUS}}\n| RD1-team14='''[[Kathy Parashis]]'''\n| RD1-score14='''4'''\n\n| RD1-seed15={{flagicon|FIN}}\n| RD1-team15='''Riitta Koskinen'''\n| RD1-score15='''4'''\n| RD1-seed16={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team16=Tracey Warren\n| RD1-score16=3\n\n| RD1-seed17={{flagicon|SCO}}\n| RD1-team17='''Julie Gillespie'''\n| RD1-score17='''4'''\n| RD1-seed18={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team18=Louise Leskevicius\n| RD1-score18=0\n\n| RD1-seed19={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team19=[[Katie Henrick]]\n| RD1-score19=0\n| RD1-seed20={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team20='''Clare Rodgers'''\n| RD1-score20='''4'''\n\n| RD1-seed21={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team21='''Martina Lumsden'''\n| RD1-score21='''4'''\n| RD1-seed22={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team22=Doreen Buckton\n| RD1-score22=0\n\n| RD1-seed23={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team23='''Gaye Jones'''\n| RD1-score23='''4'''\n| RD1-seed24={{flagicon|FIN}}\n| RD1-team24=Tuija Tiihonen\n| RD1-score24=0\n\n| RD1-seed25={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team25='''Mary Talbot'''\n| RD1-score25='''4'''\n| RD1-seed26={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team26=Nicola Barker\n| RD1-score26=0\n\n| RD1-seed27={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team27='''Rachel Ozier'''\n| RD1-score27=[[Walkover|w.o.]]\n| RD1-seed28={{flagicon|CAN}}\n| RD1-team28=Anita Morra\n| RD1-score28=scr.\n\n| RD1-seed29={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team29=Liz Jones\n| RD1-score29=3\n| RD1-seed30={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team30='''Natalie Chatfield'''\n| RD1-score30='''4'''\n\n| RD1-seed31={{flagicon|ENG}}\n| RD1-team31='''Lisa Gordon'''\n| RD1-score31='''4'''\n| RD1-seed32={{flagicon|ENG}